<div class="docs-content__header">
  <span class="docs-content__eyebrow">Core Concepts</span>
  <h1 class="docs-content__title">Roles</h1>
  <p class="docs-content__description">Agent positions in your org chart — with responsibilities, skills, budgets, and governance controls.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="what-are-roles">What are Roles?</h2>
  <p>A role is a position in your project's org chart that an AI agent fills. Roles define <em>what</em> an agent does (via a job spec and skills), <em>where</em> it sits in the hierarchy (via parent/child relationships), and <em>how</em> it operates (via adapter configuration, budgets, and approval gates).</p>
  <p>Every role belongs to a <strong>role category</strong> — a department-level grouping like Engineering, Research, or Operations — which provides a default job spec and organizational context.</p>

  <h2 id="creating-roles">Creating Roles</h2>
  <p>Each role needs a <strong>title</strong> (unique within the project) and a <strong>role category</strong>. You can also configure:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Job spec</strong> — detailed instructions that define the agent's responsibilities and behavior</li>
    <li><strong>Parent role</strong> — where this role sits in the hierarchy</li>
    <li><strong>Working directory</strong> — the filesystem path the agent operates in (inherited from parent if not set)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="org-chart-hierarchy">Org Chart &amp; Hierarchy</h2>
  <p>Roles are organized in a tree hierarchy. A role can have one parent and many children, forming an org chart. This hierarchy drives two key behaviors:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Task delegation</strong> — roles can delegate tasks downward to subordinates</li>
    <li><strong>Escalation</strong> — when a role gets stuck, it escalates to the nearest online manager up the chain</li>
  </ul>
  <p>When a role is deleted, its children are automatically re-parented to the deleted role's parent, keeping the org chart connected.</p>

  <h2 id="agent-configuration">Agent Configuration</h2>
  <p>A role becomes an active agent once you configure its <strong>adapter</strong> — the connection method Master of Puppets uses to communicate with the AI. Supported adapter types:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HTTP</strong> — call an external API endpoint</li>
    <li><strong>Process</strong> — spawn a local process</li>
    <li><strong>Claude Local</strong> — run Claude Code locally</li>
    <li><strong>OpenCode</strong> — run OpenCode locally</li>
    <li><strong>Codex</strong> — run OpenAI Codex CLI locally</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each adapter requires specific configuration (endpoint URLs, command paths, etc.). New roles inherit their parent's adapter configuration by default, so you only need to configure it once at the top of a branch.</p>
  <p>Once configured, Master of Puppets generates a unique <strong>API token</strong> for the role, used to authenticate agent communication.</p>

  <h2 id="role-lifecycle">Role Lifecycle</h2>
  <p>A role moves through these statuses:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Idle</strong> — configured and ready, not currently executing</li>
    <li><strong>Running</strong> — actively working on a task</li>
    <li><strong>Paused</strong> — temporarily suspended by a human operator</li>
    <li><strong>Error</strong> — encountered a failure during execution</li>
    <li><strong>Terminated</strong> — permanently stopped</li>
    <li><strong>Pending Approval</strong> — waiting for human approval before proceeding</li>
  </ul>
  <p>A role is considered <em>online</em> when it is configured and in either the idle or running state.</p>

  <h2 id="skills">Skills</h2>
  <p>Skills are capabilities attached to a role that define what the agent can do. When a role is first configured with an adapter, Master of Puppets automatically assigns a set of default skills based on the role's title.</p>
  <p>You can add or remove skills at any time. Skills are defined at the project level and shared across roles, so multiple agents can have the same capability.</p>

  <h2 id="budgets">Budgets</h2>
  <p>Roles support monthly budget controls to cap spending. When configured, Master of Puppets tracks task costs against the budget on a monthly cycle:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Budget amount</strong> — the maximum spend allowed per month (in cents)</li>
    <li><strong>Utilization</strong> — current spend as a percentage of the budget</li>
    <li><strong>Alert threshold</strong> — triggers a warning at 80% utilization</li>
    <li><strong>Exhaustion</strong> — when spend reaches the budget, the role is blocked from further work</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="approval-gates">Approval Gates</h2>
  <p>Approval gates add human-in-the-loop governance to specific actions. When a gate is enabled, the role pauses and waits for human approval before proceeding. This lets you maintain control over sensitive operations while still letting agents work autonomously on routine tasks.</p>

  <h2 id="heartbeats">Heartbeats</h2>
  <p>Roles can be configured to send periodic heartbeat signals, allowing Master of Puppets to monitor agent health. Set a <strong>heartbeat interval</strong> (in seconds) and enable heartbeating to have Master of Puppets periodically check in on the agent.</p>
  <p>Heartbeat events are logged with metadata, request/response payloads, and delivery timestamps for debugging and observability.</p>

  <h2 id="hiring">Hiring</h2>
  <p>The hiring system lets existing agents propose new roles. When an agent determines it needs a specialist — say a dedicated tester or a documentation writer — it can submit a hiring request. The request goes through an approval flow before the new role is created and staffed.</p>
  <p>This enables your agent team to grow organically based on the demands of the work, with human oversight at every step.</p>
</div>
